data.content:
Ubuntu	Windows
dual-boot setup, system flexibility
Both Windows and Ubuntu are set up to run on the same machine, providing flexibility through dual-booting, allowing the user to switch between two different operating systems.

BIOS/UEFI	Ubuntu
boot configuration, installation process
Understanding BIOS/UEFI settings is necessary for correctly installing Ubuntu because it affects how the computer boots and recognizes bootable devices.

Secure Boot	Ubuntu
installation interference, security standard
For the successful installation of Ubuntu, Secure Boot may need to be disabled in the system's firmware settings, as it can interfere with non-signed operating systems loading.

GRUB bootloader	Windows/Ubuntu
boot management, system access
The GRUB bootloader is configured during Ubuntu installation to allow users to choose between Windows and Ubuntu at startup, managing access to both systems.

Rufus	USB Drive
boot creation, installation preparation
Rufus is used to create bootable USB drives by writing an ISO file onto them, which is essential for installing Ubuntu.

Data Backup	External hard drive/cloud storage
data protection, backup solution
Using external hard drives or cloud services ensures data protection during the dual-boot setup process by providing a means to recover important files if needed.

Disk Space Management	File Explorer
space assessment, partitioning preparation
File Explorer is used to check available disk space on the main hard drive before allocating space for Ubuntu installation.

Partition Creation	Windows Disk Management
partition resizing, system modification
Windows Disk Management allows users to shrink existing partitions and create unallocated space needed for installing Ubuntu.

GRUB	Ubuntu
bootloader configuration, dual-boot setup
Ubuntu installation requires configuring GRUB as the bootloader to allow selection between Ubuntu and Windows during system startup.

GRUB	Windows
operating system detection, boot menu appearance<SEP>operating system integration, boot menu setup
GRUB needs to correctly identify Windows during its scan so that it can be added to the boot menu for selection alongside Ubuntu.<SEP>Windows must be recognized by GRUB for it to appear in the boot menu when using a dual-boot setup with Ubuntu.

BIOS	Ubuntu
boot priority configuration, dual-boot management
The BIOS settings can determine which operating system boots by default, and they must be configured to recognize Ubuntu as an option in a dual-boot setup.

Boot-Repair	GRUB
boot issue resolution, bootloader repair
Boot-Repair is used as a solution tool when GRUB does not automatically detect installed operating systems like Windows in a dual-boot configuration with Ubuntu.

Ubuntu	Wi-Fi
network connectivity check, post-installation verification
After installing Ubuntu, Wi-Fi should be verified to ensure the system's networking capabilities are functioning properly.

Ubuntu	display resolution
visual settings adjustment, user experience enhancement
Following Ubuntu installation, it is important to check and adjust the display resolution to suit user preferences or requirements.

Ubuntu	software settings
configuration check, system optimization
After installing Ubuntu, software settings should be reviewed and configured according to the user's needs for optimal system performance.
